<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by Melchior on 04-20-2001 04:19 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Given level 60 and the +mana bonuses on your gear, this formula seems to fit...

int*11 + min(176,int)-176 - 12*(min(199,int)-199) + 252

Bleh, that notation is awkward...let me try this way:
11 mana/int up to int=200, with a bonus 1 mana/int for each int with 176&lt;int&lt;200.
Plus 252 (combination of +mana gear and some base constant?).

Maybe the 176&lt;int&lt;200 thing is supposed to make 175 special (the same way 75 and 100 are supposed to be special), but they got the inequality wrong?
...And maybe got the inequality wrong on the upper end too, not giving a bonus point at 200?  176&lt;=int&lt;=200 would make a lot of sense...
Is the 3600 mana not taking specialization into account by any chance (in other words using 3600 mana worth of spells, but having them only cost about 2/3 the mana)?

Now I'm curious...I'll go do some tests after I get some sleep.</TEXTAREA>
